oduction to the study of justice in the European, North American and Russian Arctic, this collection considers the responsibilities and failures of justice for environment and society in the region. Inspired by key thinkers in justice, this book highlights the real and practical consequences of postcolonial legacies, climate change and the regions’ incorporation into the international political economy. The chapters feature liberal, cosmopolitan, feminist, as well as critical justice perspectives from experts with decades of research experience in the Arctic. Moving from a critique of current failures, the collection champions an ethical and sustainable future for Arctic development and governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aBadyina, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Aaron M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDannevig, Halvor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreng Dale, Ragnhild, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolubchikov, Oleg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerman, Agatha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngimundarson, Jón Haukur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoona, Juha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoona, Tanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarsen, Joan Nymand, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCauley, Darren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMels, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhlsson, Joh